05166nam a22006735i 9781400840762DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20112002nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008407627 a10.1515/97814008407622doi  a(DE-B1597)453590  a(OCoLC)979582577  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aEDU0400002bisacsh04a378.1/982221 aMassey, Douglas S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Source of the River :bThe Social Origins of Freshmen at America's Selective Colleges and Universities /cGarvey Lundy, Mary J. Fischer, Douglas S. Massey, Camille Z. Charles.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2011] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b66 tables. 19 line illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe William G. Bowen Series ;v6100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Tables and Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tONE. The Puzzle of Minority Underachievement -- tTWO. Sample and Methodology -- tTHREE. Family Origins -- tFour. Neighborhood Background -- tFIVE. Prior Educational Experiences -- tSIX. The Social World of High School -- tSEVEN. Racial Identity and Attitudes -- tEIGHT. Pathways to Preparation -- tNINE. Sink or Swim: The First Semester -- tTEN. Lessons Learned -- tAppendix A. Survey of College Life and Experience: First-Wave Instrument -- tAppendix B. Construction of Social Scales -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAfrican Americans and Latinos earn lower grades and drop out of college more often than whites or Asians. Yet thirty years after deliberate minority recruitment efforts began, we still don't know why. In The Shape of the River, William Bowen and Derek Bok documented the benefits of affirmative action for minority students, their communities, and the nation at large. But they also found that too many failed to achieve academic success. In The Source of the River, Douglas Massey and his colleagues investigate the roots of minority underperformance in selective colleges and universities. They explain how such factors as neighborhood, family, peer group, and early schooling influence the academic performance of students from differing racial and ethnic origins and differing social classes. Drawing on a major new source of data--the National Longitudinal Survey of Freshmen--the authors undertake a comprehensive analysis of the diverse pathways by which whites, African Americans, Latinos, and Asians enter American higher education. Theirs is the first study to document the different characteristics that students bring to campus and to trace out the influence of these differences on later academic performance. They show that black and Latino students do not enter college disadvantaged by a lack of self-esteem. In fact, overconfidence is more common than low self-confidence among some minority students. Despite this, minority students are adversely affected by racist stereotypes of intellectual inferiority. Although academic preparation is the strongest predictor of college performance, shortfalls in academic preparation are themselves largely a matter of socioeconomic disadvantage and racial segregation. Presenting important new findings, The Source of the River documents the ongoing power of race to shape the life chances of America's young people, even among the most talented and able.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 7aEDUCATION / Philosophy, Theory & Social Aspects.2bisacsh1 aCharles, Camille Z., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aLundy, Garvey, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Pa